nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Beta  Ask  Recap|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   A quick recap of what we looked at last week, which was Beta, Precision's equivalent of Blackwood, asking about partner's GENERAL level of Controls.

An Ace = 2 Controls and a King = 1 Control, and Beta asks exactly how many Controls partner's hand contains.

The main places where a bid is Beta are as follows: 
^c@2
(1) In "natural" bidding sequences, 4@C is usually Beta unless Clubs is the agreed or a potential trump suit, in which case 4@D can be Beta.

(2) In Asking Bid sequences, 4@C/@D can also be Beta if required.

(3) Whenever we've agreed a trump suit by means of an Asking Bid and response, then a relay in the next suit up over the response is Relay Beta (ignoring the agreed trump suit, and ignoring NT's if a Minor suit agreed).

(4) Whenever we've shown a shortage, directly or indirectly (eg: Splinter, 4441 shape, etc), then a bid of the SHORT suit can be Beta.

(5) A Relay over a POSITIVE response to 1@C (not 1@C - 1@H - 1@S) is Low - level Beta.

(6) There are some other specific circumstances where a bid can be Beta, but the above covers 90% of circumstances.

^b@2
Next are the scales.|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Beta  Scales|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   There are various "Scales" for Beta, depending on Responder's KNOWN HCP strength and/or KNOWN level of Controls: The "Normal" scale is used when Responder's strength is unknown, or is KNOWN to be Intermediate (11 - 15): Stepped responses show 0-2, 3, 4, 5 etc.

The "Weak" scale is used when Responder is KNOWN to be 0-10 (eg: passed hand, Weak 2 opened, 1@D response to 1@C) or when they are KNOWN to have 0-3 controls (eg: 1 or 3-step response to an earlier Alpha, 1-step response to an earlier Beta).

Stepped responses show   0, 1, 2, 3, 4 etc.

The "Special Weak" scale is used ONLY when Responder is a passed hand and Opener uses a LOW - LEVEL Beta over a positive response to their 1@C Opening.

Stepped responses show   0-1, 2, 3, 4 etc.     eg: 

^dPass  -  1@C - 1@S - 1NT     uses the Special Weak Scale.

The "Strong" scale is used when Responder is KNOWN to be 16+ or, more commonly, when they are KNOWN to have 4+ Controls (2 or 4 - step response to an earlier Alpha).

Stepped responses are   0-4, 5, 6, 7 etc.

There are two other ranges (Super and Range), but they occur VERY infrequently, especially in the "simple" version of this system.

You can look them up on the website if you're interested.

Any questions on Beta before we move onto this week's lesson?|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|The  Alpha Ask|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   The Asking Bid we're going to deal with today is called Alpha.

Alpha is a bid that asks Responder about their support for the Captain's primary suit.

It also obtains information about Responder's general level of controls.

Alpha is ALWAYS the FIRST Asking bid in an Asking Bid sequence if it is used at all.

If the first Asking Bid is NOT Alpha, then Alpha will not be used in that sequence at all (never!).

The most common place where Alpha is used is after a positive response to a 1@C Opener.

Here a simple bid in a new suit is Alpha.   eg: 

^c 1@C - 1@H - 2@D      is  Alpha in Diamonds.

There are 3 specific occasions when this is not true, which is when the positive response to 1@C is 1NT, 2@C, or 2@D, and Opener wants to make an Alpha Ask in the suit immediately above that bid.   eg:

^c 1@C - 2@C - 2@D      is NOT Alpha but a different Ask (Beta).|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   (so far we have...)

^c 1@C - 1@H - 2@D      is  Alpha in Diamonds.
^c 1@C - 2@C - 2@D      is NOT Alpha but a different Ask (Beta).

So  2NT  is used and becomes Alpha in the suit immediately above the positive response (ie: the relay suit), so 
^c@2
1@C - 2@C - 2NT ^g is Alpha in Diamonds.

^bmore examples

1@C - 1@H - 1@S ^g is Alpha in Spades.

1@C - 2@C - 2@H ^g is Alpha in Hearts.

1@C - 2@D - 2NT ^g is Alpha in Hearts   (because   1@C - 2@D - 2@H   is Beta).

1@C - 1@S - 2@D ^g is Alpha in Diamonds.
^b@2
The other main situation where Alpha occurs is a jump-shift over an INTERMEDIATE Precision Opening of   1@D,  1NT  or  2@C.   eg:
^c@2
1@D ^d -  3@C ^g is Alpha in Clubs

1NT ^d -  3@S ^g is Alpha in Spades

2@C ^d -  3@H ^g is Alpha in Hearts|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   It's worth stressing that we do NOT use Alpha over Major Suit openings, so 

^c1@S - 3@C        is a fit-showing jump-Shift rather than Alpha.

The only other situation you will ever see Alpha being used is in the Complex version of the system, and I don't propose to confuse things by going into that now.

So Alpha is always used to kick off an Asking Bid sequence (but it's not the only way to do that).

In practice this Asking Bid is NOT used as often as you might think in  1@C  sequences.

The most common situation is where the strong hand has a distributional 2-suiter with no support or tolerance for a suit that Partner might have shown.

You will find as we go on that it is more common for a  1@C  Opener to use the low-level Beta and then to use a Theta or Iota Ask than it is for them to use Alpha.

This is because Beta is more "precise" than Alpha where controls are concerned (more likely to get a range response to Alpha) and Theta/Iota gets more precise information about Responder's trump holding.

One exception to this can be where Responder is a passed hand and the Special Weak Beta would be in operation.

Now the low-level Beta (using the Special Weak Scale) and then Theta/Iota might prove to be an over-expensive option and sometimes Opener judges to use Alpha instead.   So 

^c Pass  -  1@C - 1@S - 2@H(Alpha)    might be preferred to 

^c Pass  -  1@C - 1@S - 1NT(Beta)    because the Beta response will be on the SPECIAL WEAK scale,

which in turn might mean that Opener would not be able to ask in Hearts at the 2-level (ie: if Responder has 3 or more Controls).  Apart from these two situations, Alpha simply does not occur (unless you're using the Complex version of the system).|
