fp|t-title|at|Responses  to  Alpha|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   The responses to Alpha are as follows (A 3-step or greater response agrees the suit): 

^f Remember   ^*bH^*n    =    A, K or Q      (never J or 10)
^c@2
1  step  ^e No Support  (less than Hxx or xxxx)     ^m and ^o 0-3   ^p controls 
2  steps ^e No Support                             ^m and ^o  4+    ^p controls 
3  steps ^e       Support  (at least Hxx or xxxx)    ^m and ^o 0-3  ^p controls       agrees trumps  (as do following)
4  steps ^e       Support  (exactly Hxx or xxxx)    ^m and ^o  4+     ^p controls 
5  steps ^e       GOOD 4-card Support  (Hxxx or better)  and^o  4     ^p controls 
6  steps ^e       GOOD 4-card Support  ^m and              ^o  5     ^p controls 
7  steps ^e       GOOD 4-card Support  ^m and              ^o  6     ^p controls,
   etc...
^b@2
Note that the qualification for agreeing the suit has nothing whatever to do with the number of controls held, solely possession of sufficient trump support, so a 1 or 2-step response to Alpha is "Negative" and a 3-step or greater response is "Positive".

The response to Alpha ALWAYS affects the range used in any subsequent Beta Ask or whether it's available at all, so after a 1 or 3-step response the WEAK Beta scale is used, and after a 2 or 4-step response to Alpha, the STRONG Beta scale is used.

Clearly if the response to Alpha shows an exact number of controls (eg: a 5-step or greater response), then there will be no need for a Beta Ask at all.

Please also note that a holding such as Hx or xxx does NOT qualify as "support" in response to an Alpha ask, but should the Captain choose to make a Repeat Alpha Ask (ie: Theta) in the same suit, then a holding such as Hx or xxx WILL now agree the suit (more on that in a moment).

Any questions on the responses to Alpha?                      OK then   back to   Teach 1|
