fp|t-title|at|After  a  Negative|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  If the Captain gets a "negative" response to Alpha, they can make a repeat ask in the SAME suit to ascertain Responder's exact holding.

This is a  ^*bTheta Ask^*n.    We will not be covering Theta in detail today, but there are notes on it on the website.

If a repeat Alpha (ie: Theta) in the same suit is used then a Theta response showing Hx or xxx agrees the suit, as I said earlier.

If the Captain gets a "negative" response to Alpha, they can also make a repeat ask in a DIFFERENT suit to ascertain Responder's exact holding there.

This is an  ^*bIota Ask^*n  rather than  Theta.   We will not be covering  Iota  today, but see the notes on it on the website.

^cWe will come to  Theta  and  Iota  in a few weeks.

The reason for the difference is that if partner has no good support for the first suit they are notionally more likely to have "adequate" support for the second suit, so we can afford to try to save space a little (Iota is a slightly collapsed version of Theta).

Because we're asking in a NEW suit, the "normal" rules for agreeing the suit apply (ie: A response showing HH, Hxx or xxxx in the suit is required to agree it).

Agreeing a suit with HH is only possible with Theta or Iota, because HH is an alternative to Hxx in those scales.


Any questions on repeat Alpha Asks in the same or a different suit?|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Beta  after  a  Positive|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   If Alpha receives a POSITIVE response of 3 or 4 steps (NOT greater than 4 steps), then a relay in the next suit up (not trumps) over the Alpha response is  ^*bBeta^*n  on the appropriate scale.

If the next suit up is the agreed trump suit then we ignore trumps and go to the next suit above THAT for the Relay Beta.

Similarly if Alpha has been used in a MINOR suit and the Relay over the Alpha Response is 3NT (NOT 2NT), then we ignore NT's and move to the next available new suit over that (not the trump suit).  Thus

^c 1@C - 1@S - 2@H(Alpha) - 3@C - 3@D   is Beta,    but over

^c 1@C - 1@S - 2@H(Alpha) - 3@D       we skip 3@H (which is an Asking Bid, ^*bSigma^*n) and use  3@S  as the  ^*bRelay Beta^*n.

Similarly, over a sequence like

^c 1@C - 2@C - 2NT(Alpha in Diamonds) - 3@S,   now  4@C  is Beta and  3NT  is ostensibly "to play" 

^d(but probably  carries the nuance   "I have a minimum 1@C Opener.  
^iIf you only have 4 Controls let's play here but if you have more, then carry on" ).

Lastly, I mentioned Sigma above.

We'll look at that properly later in the Series, but worth mentioning here that Sigma is an immediate repeat of the agreed trump suit BELOW game level after a positive response to Alpha.

It is used to check on trump solidity and asks Responder to clarify their exact holding in the suit.|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


nt|^z@3^b@2|at|^^^^|
fp|t-title|at|Checking  on  Trump  Solidity|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|   You'll have noticed that a holding of xxxx is enough for a positive response to Alpha, but there's a big difference between xxxx and HHxxx and sometimes it's critical for Opener to be able to check on trump solidity.

Please note that if Alpha (or any other  ^*bTrump^*n  Asking Bid, for that matter) receives a ^*bPOSITIVE^*n response, ALL the Trump Asking Bids (except Sigma) automatically become unavailable, and the ONLY Asking Bids that are still "on the menu" are Beta and Epsilon.

This way we know that    1@C - 1@H - 1@S - 2@D - 3@C    is  ^*bEpsilon^*n, NOT some other Trump Asking Bid.

Any questions? 


